scale repository of skaldic verse. Morkinskinna also includes many semi-independent tales that recount the adventures of individual Icelanders at the Norwegian court. These tales, with their often humorous or ironic inflections, shift the focus of the chronicle from the deeds of the kings to the Icelandic perception of Norwegian royalty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aFiction & Short Stories. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aFICTION / Sagas.2bisacsh  ascandanavian history, saga fiction, icelandic history, icelandic folklore, rotten parchment, medieval norway, norwegian history.1 aAndersson, Theodore M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGade, Kari Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, Patrick J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172061140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501720611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501720611/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles